0
00:01:20,800 --> 00:01:22,400
Ladies and gentlemen

1
00:01:22,720 --> 00:01:23,816
what you're about to witness

2
00:01:23,840 --> 00:01:24,920
is the next evolution

3
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:26,400
in military engagement.

4
00:01:26,480 --> 00:01:29,640
A machine that operates
with surgical precision.

5
00:01:29,720 --> 00:01:32,440
And in a world where every action
is under the media microscope

6
00:01:32,520 --> 00:01:34,600
this technology will allow our nation

7
00:01:34,680 --> 00:01:38,240
and its allies the means
to act quickly, decisively

8
00:01:38,320 --> 00:01:40,480
and without the specter
of political blowback.

9
00:01:41,840 --> 00:01:43,800
Madam Secretary,
glad you could join us.

10
00:01:43,880 --> 00:01:45,096
Would you mind explaining to me

11
00:01:45,120 --> 00:01:47,160
why you're conducting
a joint military operation

12
00:01:47,240 --> 00:01:48,240
without my approval?

13
00:01:48,320 --> 00:01:50,000
I appreciate
it looks like that, Shelley

14
00:01:50,080 --> 00:01:52,160
but we're here strictly
as technical support.

15
00:01:52,240 --> 00:01:54,320
The mission's being conducted
by Saudi intelligence.

16
00:01:54,400 --> 00:01:56,360
We're merely loaning out the asset.

17
00:01:56,440 --> 00:01:58,720
What are you talking about?
What asset?

18
00:02:28,600 --> 00:02:29,600
Eyes are up.

19
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:53,080
What you just saw was not only
a test of our technological prowess

20
00:03:53,160 --> 00:03:55,080
but a clear message to our enemies.

21
00:03:55,160 --> 00:03:57,960
If the 21st century
wants another arms race

22
00:03:58,040 --> 00:04:00,480
you better goddamn believe
we intend to win it.

23
00:04:03,280 --> 00:04:05,280
- What the hell was that?
- She just shot Trapathi.

24
00:04:07,520 --> 00:04:09,720
- Someone, get her on the comms.
- She's not responding.

25
00:04:09,760 --> 00:04:11,616
What the hell is going on, Sattler?
Are we being hacked?

26
00:04:11,640 --> 00:04:14,480
Everybody stay calm, okay?
One of you shut this down.

27
00:04:14,560 --> 00:04:15,840
We can't. We don't have control.

28
00:04:15,880 --> 00:04:17,320
Well, then, who the hell does?

29
00:04:22,400 --> 00:04:25,120
<i>You are in violation
of your orders, Amelia.</i>

30
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:27,280
<i>Confirm your objective.</i>

31
00:04:31,320 --> 00:04:33,520
But that would spoil the surprise.

32
00:04:38,360 --> 00:04:39,720
Before we start

33
00:04:39,800 --> 00:04:41,640
I want you to know
that nothing you say here

34
00:04:41,720 --> 00:04:43,320
will get your aunt in any trouble.

35
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:46,320
I'm no longer here
by order of the court.

36
00:04:46,400 --> 00:04:49,360
I just wanted to check in
and see how you're doing.

37
00:04:49,760 --> 00:04:51,320
Given everything that's happened.

38
00:04:52,240 --> 00:04:53,440
I mean...

39
00:04:55,440 --> 00:04:57,360
I guess it could have been
a lot worse.

40
00:04:58,000 --> 00:04:59,600
<i>A live launch for a new toy has</i>

41
00:04:59,680 --> 00:05:01,400
<i>devolved into a murderous rampage.</i>

42
00:05:01,480 --> 00:05:03,080
{\an5}<i>Toy designer Gemma Forrester
appeared</i>

43
00:05:03,160 --> 00:05:04,680
<i>in the Seattle District Court today</i>

44
00:05:04,760 --> 00:05:06,880
<i>facing charges
of reckless endangerment.</i>

45
00:05:06,960 --> 00:05:08,080
A lot of people blame Gemma

46
00:05:08,160 --> 00:05:09,400
for what Megan did.

47
00:05:09,880 --> 00:05:11,800
For a long time she blamed herself.

48
00:05:12,120 --> 00:05:13,240
But the more she went on TV

49
00:05:13,320 --> 00:05:14,680
to talk about what happened

50
00:05:14,760 --> 00:05:16,480
the more she realized
she had an opportunity

51
00:05:16,560 --> 00:05:17,936
to turn it into something positive.

52
00:05:17,960 --> 00:05:20,000
This is about a world in crisis.

53
00:05:20,160 --> 00:05:22,480
Outsourcing our parental duties
to devices.

54
00:05:22,560 --> 00:05:26,000
Plowing our kids' minds with
electronically charged dopamine hits.

55
00:05:26,080 --> 00:05:28,400
You wouldn't give your child cocaine.

56
00:05:28,840 --> 00:05:30,840
Why would you give them a smartphone?

57
00:05:33,320 --> 00:05:34,800
<i>And that's how she met Christian.</i>

58
00:05:37,160 --> 00:05:39,160
- Hi, Gemma. Hi.
- Yep.

59
00:05:39,400 --> 00:05:40,400
Christian Bradley.

60
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:44,120
<i>He runs a foundation that
warns people about the dangers of AI.</i>

61
00:05:44,640 --> 00:05:45,640
<i>They try to convince</i>

62
00:05:45,720 --> 00:05:47,056
<i>politicians here and around the world</i>

63
00:05:47,080 --> 00:05:48,760
<i>to make safer laws around it.</i>

64
00:05:48,840 --> 00:05:50,096
<i>So that what happened with Megan</i>

65
00:05:50,120 --> 00:05:51,280
<i>doesn't happen again.</i>

66
00:05:53,760 --> 00:05:56,480
<i>Gemma still believes technology
can be used for good.</i>

67
00:05:58,480 --> 00:06:01,400
<i>Just that kids shouldn't spend
so much time around it.</i>

68
00:06:04,520 --> 00:06:07,080
But she always makes a point
of explaining the reasons why.

69
00:06:07,160 --> 00:06:10,400
And so as it turned out,
companies were using Section 230

70
00:06:10,480 --> 00:06:13,760
as a way to skirt the law and
monetize the attention of children

71
00:06:13,840 --> 00:06:16,040
with no regard
for their mental health.

72
00:06:16,120 --> 00:06:17,640
And how do you feel about that?

73
00:06:17,720 --> 00:06:20,800
I think not being on a device
frees you up to try other things.

74
00:06:27,080 --> 00:06:28,280
Helps you make new friends.

75
00:06:29,840 --> 00:06:33,080
Thanks to your dork mom, we just
had our phones taken off the bus.

76
00:06:33,160 --> 00:06:35,440
Guess I'll have to find
other ways to amuse myself.

77
00:06:36,080 --> 00:06:37,280
And you know what else?

78
00:06:37,360 --> 00:06:39,680
You're not gonna have
that weird janky doll to protect you.

79
00:06:42,280 --> 00:06:45,680
I guess you're right.
But let me ask you this, Sapphire.

80
00:06:46,160 --> 00:06:47,160
Who's protecting you?

81
00:06:47,640 --> 00:06:48,960
So you think you're tough?

82
00:06:51,440 --> 00:06:52,880
I sent you to Aikido

83
00:06:52,960 --> 00:06:55,840
because it is the least aggressive
form of martial arts.

84
00:06:55,920 --> 00:06:57,296
And we've talked
about the merits of using

85
00:06:57,320 --> 00:06:58,640
Steven Seagal as a role model.

86
00:06:58,720 --> 00:07:01,160
I'm not saying
we don't have our problems.

87
00:07:01,240 --> 00:07:03,760
But the important thing is that
we get through them together.

88
00:07:05,800 --> 00:07:07,320
Just like we said we would.

89
00:07:07,800 --> 00:07:12,000
(French) So, both human rights
and the government are responsible.

90
00:07:12,080 --> 00:07:15,240
(French) So, having
your support means a lot.

91
00:07:24,920 --> 00:07:26,680
So, after what happened with M3gan

92
00:07:26,760 --> 00:07:29,320
our team went through something
of a philosophical shift.

93
00:07:29,400 --> 00:07:32,840
And while Gemma has obviously
become a strong voice for regulation

94
00:07:32,920 --> 00:07:35,720
our company is still very much
focused on innovation

95
00:07:35,800 --> 00:07:38,600
but with a specific view
towards socially conscious products

96
00:07:38,680 --> 00:07:40,800
that move humanity
in the right direction.

97
00:07:40,880 --> 00:07:42,320
So, with that in mind

98
00:07:42,400 --> 00:07:45,080
I'd like to present to you
our flagship invention

99
00:07:47,520 --> 00:07:49,360
the "Exoskeletor," Model One.

100
00:07:51,880 --> 00:07:53,400
Cole, this is Niles Keller.

101
00:07:53,480 --> 00:07:54,480
I know.

102
00:07:56,120 --> 00:07:57,520
You wanna come say hi?

103
00:07:57,800 --> 00:07:59,720
I want to come and say hi. Yes.

104
00:08:00,160 --> 00:08:02,120
Can you, yeah, Tess,
just come here for a second?

105
00:08:02,800 --> 00:08:03,880
Excuse me.

106
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:06,480
- What's happening?
- It's frozen.

107
00:08:06,560 --> 00:08:07,760
When you walked out, it froze.

108
00:08:07,840 --> 00:08:09,240
I cannot get my body to move.

109
00:08:09,320 --> 00:08:11,200
Okay, just... I'm gonna reboot.

110
00:08:11,280 --> 00:08:13,080
No, no, no, Tess,
you don't understand.

111
00:08:13,160 --> 00:08:14,400
I have to use the bathroom.

112
00:08:14,480 --> 00:08:15,480
No! No... no.

113
00:08:15,560 --> 00:08:16,680
- Both.
- No!

114
00:08:16,760 --> 00:08:18,056
We've already wasted his time
waiting for Gemma.

115
00:08:18,080 --> 00:08:19,640
We have ten minutes
to turn this around.

116
00:08:22,600 --> 00:08:24,520
- We're not gonna make it.
- We're gonna make it.

117
00:08:24,600 --> 00:08:26,080
Why don't you just
take the short cut?

118
00:08:26,120 --> 00:08:28,720
'Cause I don't need an algorithm
to tell me how to drive. Okay?

119
00:08:33,960 --> 00:08:35,720
Okay.

120
00:08:35,800 --> 00:08:38,240
There we go! That feels better.

121
00:08:38,320 --> 00:08:40,880
So, I'm walking over,
as you can see...

122
00:08:43,960 --> 00:08:46,360
So, we see the suit
as a real gamechanger

123
00:08:46,440 --> 00:08:48,600
not only in helping
those with limited function

124
00:08:48,680 --> 00:08:51,160
but also in addressing
occupational overuse syndrome

125
00:08:51,240 --> 00:08:53,640
for laborers, factory workers...

126
00:08:53,720 --> 00:08:55,360
Right. In the next five years

127
00:08:55,440 --> 00:08:56,960
they say half the industrial sector

128
00:08:57,040 --> 00:08:59,040
is in danger
of losing their job to robots

129
00:08:59,120 --> 00:09:01,080
because machines never
experience fatigue.

130
00:09:01,160 --> 00:09:02,920
But what if the same
could be said for us?

131
00:09:04,600 --> 00:09:08,720
Right now, I'm only using 20%
of my body's muscular function.

132
00:09:09,160 --> 00:09:13,880
And if that's too much, well,
I could always take a quick siesta.

133
00:09:14,800 --> 00:09:17,880
So our hope is, you don't have
to fear a robot revolution

134
00:09:17,960 --> 00:09:19,160
when you can compete with it.

135
00:09:20,120 --> 00:09:21,680
That sounds like
a pretty good tag line.

136
00:09:21,840 --> 00:09:23,000
So how does it work?

137
00:09:23,080 --> 00:09:26,800
Well, the suit has its own
internal myoelectric receptors

138
00:09:26,880 --> 00:09:29,200
that respond to
each muscle contraction.

139
00:09:33,600 --> 00:09:35,200
So sorry, I'm late...

140
00:09:36,600 --> 00:09:38,760
I told you we needed
to stress test the sensors.

141
00:09:38,840 --> 00:09:40,136
You know what would have been great?

142
00:09:40,160 --> 00:09:41,720
If you'd actually been here.

143
00:09:41,800 --> 00:09:43,400
I thought by having
the lab in your house

144
00:09:43,440 --> 00:09:45,080
it'd be a lot harder to show up late

145
00:09:45,160 --> 00:09:47,280
and yet somehow you managed it.

146
00:09:47,360 --> 00:09:48,520
Cole's right.

147
00:09:48,600 --> 00:09:49,976
I mean, I don't want to get
in the way of the work

148
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:51,056
you're doing at the foundation

149
00:09:51,080 --> 00:09:53,280
but the reality is
you are stretched pretty thin.

150
00:09:53,360 --> 00:09:55,496
Okay, can we just not do this
in front of my niece, please?

151
00:09:55,520 --> 00:09:58,320
Cady, do you think it's possible
you could be somewhere else?

152
00:09:58,400 --> 00:10:00,040
Yeah, but you should
come look at this.

153
00:10:00,120 --> 00:10:01,400
I think you were hacked.

154
00:10:01,480 --> 00:10:02,480
What?

155
00:10:05,280 --> 00:10:06,680
Oh, Jesus, she's right.

156
00:10:06,760 --> 00:10:08,496
There's stray commands
all over the source code.

157
00:10:08,520 --> 00:10:10,240
We haven't even
gone public with this yet.

158
00:10:10,320 --> 00:10:11,760
I mean, who would want to do that?

159
00:10:12,200 --> 00:10:13,200
Knock, knock.

160
00:10:14,400 --> 00:10:15,800
Pardon my interruption.

161
00:10:15,880 --> 00:10:16,960
Holy shit.

162
00:10:17,240 --> 00:10:18,960
- Alton Appleton.
- Hi.

163
00:10:19,200 --> 00:10:20,840
- Sorry.
- No, no. That's okay.

164
00:10:21,520 --> 00:10:23,920
Gemma, I hope you don't mind me
popping in unannounced.

165
00:10:24,200 --> 00:10:27,120
Alton, to what do we owe
this unexpected pleasure?

166
00:10:27,200 --> 00:10:28,456
It sounds like
there was a slight snag

167
00:10:28,480 --> 00:10:29,480
with your demonstration.

168
00:10:29,560 --> 00:10:30,880
Yeah, well, we got hacked

169
00:10:30,960 --> 00:10:33,040
but you wouldn't know
anything about that, right?

170
00:10:33,120 --> 00:10:34,760
Gemma, why would
a man of my standing

171
00:10:34,840 --> 00:10:36,480
need to resort to such tactics?

172
00:10:36,560 --> 00:10:38,680
The real question is,
why have you contacted

173
00:10:38,760 --> 00:10:40,800
every philanthro-capitalist
in the Western world

174
00:10:40,880 --> 00:10:42,840
to invest in your product but me?

175
00:10:42,920 --> 00:10:44,200
I think you can figure that out.

176
00:10:44,280 --> 00:10:45,320
You know what I think?

177
00:10:45,400 --> 00:10:48,480
I think you see me
as this high-functioning billionaire

178
00:10:48,560 --> 00:10:51,080
with multiple PhDs,
and you're threatened by it.

179
00:10:51,400 --> 00:10:54,600
What you don't see is a man
who can't stand to see someone

180
00:10:54,680 --> 00:10:57,000
with your talent
slamming it in some

181
00:10:57,360 --> 00:10:59,280
excuse me, converted crack house.

182
00:10:59,360 --> 00:11:01,120
Wow, I really appreciate
your concern.

183
00:11:01,200 --> 00:11:03,680
- We're not taking outside offers...
- Sorry, Gemma, one moment.

184
00:11:04,120 --> 00:11:05,440
Murray, you're still in Monaco?

185
00:11:05,520 --> 00:11:06,840
You look like you haven't slept.

186
00:11:08,200 --> 00:11:11,840
No, no. Yeah, I've seen them.

187
00:11:11,920 --> 00:11:14,360
I still think they're too close
to Aston Martin's design.

188
00:11:14,440 --> 00:11:16,120
No, I've got them on screen now.

189
00:11:16,440 --> 00:11:18,840
I hate it. It was awful.

190
00:11:19,240 --> 00:11:21,120
I've just zoomed in
and I hate it even more.

191
00:11:21,440 --> 00:11:23,120
Listen, I'm with someone.

192
00:11:24,040 --> 00:11:25,480
No, not in that way.

193
00:11:25,880 --> 00:11:27,960
Although... I just sent you a photo.

194
00:11:28,480 --> 00:11:29,960
We'll talk about it track side, yeah?

195
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:31,760
Okay, ta-ta. Go.

196
00:11:31,840 --> 00:11:33,776
As I was saying, we really
appreciate you stopping by...

197
00:11:33,800 --> 00:11:36,440
Listen, I don't have much time,
so I'm going to cut to the chase.

198
00:11:36,520 --> 00:11:38,680
Any device that relies
on muscle signals

199
00:11:38,760 --> 00:11:40,640
is going to suffer from latency.

200
00:11:40,720 --> 00:11:42,840
It's clumsy.
To take this to the next level

201
00:11:42,920 --> 00:11:45,680
you're going to need
a direct cerebral interface.

202
00:11:46,400 --> 00:11:47,840
You're going to need my neural chip.

203
00:11:47,920 --> 00:11:49,720
Alton, you know
where I stand on this.

204
00:11:49,800 --> 00:11:51,296
We are not going to be
part of a company

205
00:11:51,320 --> 00:11:52,800
that turns people into cyborgs.

206
00:11:52,880 --> 00:11:54,480
You conducted a clinical trial

207
00:11:54,560 --> 00:11:56,800
that resulted in
30% of the test subjects

208
00:11:56,880 --> 00:11:58,040
being hospitalized.

209
00:11:58,120 --> 00:12:00,640
Well, at least I didn't use
my own niece as a guinea pig.

210
00:12:01,880 --> 00:12:05,320
The important thing is,
now we have a product that works.

211
00:12:05,400 --> 00:12:07,640
Based on what?
I haven't seen a single piece of data

212
00:12:07,720 --> 00:12:10,400
that shows it does anything other
than help you make a phone call.

213
00:12:18,800 --> 00:12:20,960
Look, I understand your reservations.

214
00:12:21,520 --> 00:12:23,480
But you can either
spend the rest of your life

215
00:12:23,560 --> 00:12:25,040
trying to fight the future

216
00:12:25,120 --> 00:12:26,680
or you can help us to shape it.

217
00:12:28,360 --> 00:12:29,560
I hope you do the latter.

218
00:12:30,760 --> 00:12:31,840
I'm not interested.

219
00:12:31,920 --> 00:12:34,200
Well, you may want to discuss that
with your colleagues.

220
00:12:34,280 --> 00:12:37,280
Listen, it's our company's
25th anniversary tomorrow.

221
00:12:37,360 --> 00:12:38,656
Why don't you see
what we're all about

222
00:12:38,680 --> 00:12:39,960
before you make any decisions?

223
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:46,240
Alton, no one is denying
the power this technology has.

224
00:12:46,320 --> 00:12:48,440
But if you put an AI
inside a human brain

225
00:12:48,520 --> 00:12:50,280
it is not going to ride shotgun.

226
00:13:15,880 --> 00:13:16,920
Hey.

227
00:13:17,720 --> 00:13:19,520
(Dutch)

228
00:13:20,680 --> 00:13:21,680
(Dutch)

229
00:13:22,920 --> 00:13:24,280
(Dutch)

230
00:13:24,880 --> 00:13:26,640
(Dutch)

231
00:13:28,520 --> 00:13:29,840
(Dutch)

232
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:02,040
<i>Breaking news tonight. Alton Appleton
takes one step for man</i>

233
00:14:02,120 --> 00:14:05,280
<i>and one giant leap
for his company's share price.</i>

234
00:14:05,360 --> 00:14:08,720
<i>Also tonight, the Senate votes
in favor of an AI regulation bill</i>

235
00:14:08,800 --> 00:14:11,760
<i>which the president is hailing
as a bipartisan victory.</i>

236
00:14:11,840 --> 00:14:13,456
<i>But what does it mean
for the tech industry?</i>

237
00:14:13,480 --> 00:14:14,680
It means nothing.

238
00:14:14,760 --> 00:14:16,296
They took our proposal
and they neutered it.

239
00:14:16,320 --> 00:14:17,896
There's not a single
actionable law in here

240
00:14:17,920 --> 00:14:19,920
that would force anyone
to behave any differently.

241
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:22,760
Your impatience in the political
process is adorable.

242
00:14:23,120 --> 00:14:24,776
Listen, change doesn't
come from Washington.

243
00:14:24,800 --> 00:14:26,360
It comes to Washington.

244
00:14:26,440 --> 00:14:29,160
This meeting with
the Chinese ambassador goes well

245
00:14:29,240 --> 00:14:30,960
they have no choice
but to pay attention.

246
00:14:34,240 --> 00:14:35,240
Cady, what are you doing?

247
00:14:35,320 --> 00:14:37,960
I'm trying to update Elsie's
operating system to the smart home.

248
00:14:38,040 --> 00:14:39,256
You wanna know why it's not updating?

249
00:14:39,280 --> 00:14:41,296
Because Alton Appleton wants you
to buy a brand new one.

250
00:14:41,320 --> 00:14:43,976
Christian's right. And also, I don't
need Elsie to open a drawer for me.

251
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:45,480
<i>Certainly, Gemma.</i>

252
00:14:48,200 --> 00:14:50,496
Before you asked, that was
not my idea. It came with the house.

253
00:14:50,520 --> 00:14:52,776
I'm just trying to figure out
how you can afford a place like this

254
00:14:52,800 --> 00:14:54,440
given that we both work
for a non-profit.

255
00:14:54,520 --> 00:14:56,400
Well, because it was obscenely cheap.

256
00:14:56,480 --> 00:14:58,576
I think the landlord must be
using it to launder money.

257
00:14:58,600 --> 00:15:00,520
I think the landlord might like you.

258
00:15:08,040 --> 00:15:09,080
Cady?

259
00:15:09,760 --> 00:15:11,440
How's... how's the new school
treating you?

260
00:15:11,480 --> 00:15:12,680
Are you settling in okay?

261
00:15:12,760 --> 00:15:15,040
- Yeah, it's awesome.
- Nice. What's your

262
00:15:15,120 --> 00:15:16,216
what's your favorite subject?

263
00:15:16,240 --> 00:15:17,400
Computer science.

264
00:15:19,080 --> 00:15:20,776
So you're gonna follow
in your aunt's footsteps?

265
00:15:20,800 --> 00:15:22,040
That's still up for discussion.

266
00:15:22,120 --> 00:15:23,776
She's actually a really
good soccer player.

267
00:15:23,800 --> 00:15:25,536
Yeah, but I'm not gonna
make a career out of it.

268
00:15:25,560 --> 00:15:26,960
Well, you could get a scholarship

269
00:15:27,040 --> 00:15:28,536
and then you could decide
what you want to do.

270
00:15:28,560 --> 00:15:29,640
I already have decided.

271
00:15:32,600 --> 00:15:33,840
Well, I think it's pretty cool.

272
00:15:34,320 --> 00:15:35,520
- You do?
- Yes.

273
00:15:36,320 --> 00:15:38,440
Look, I'm not against technology.

274
00:15:38,520 --> 00:15:40,160
I spent 15 years in cybersecurity.

275
00:15:40,240 --> 00:15:41,976
I think we need smart kids
like you running things.

276
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:43,800
Otherwise, we're gonna
end up with paperclips.

277
00:15:44,320 --> 00:15:45,920
- What?
- Paperclips.

278
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:48,880
It's how we used to joke about
instrumental convergence in college.

279
00:15:48,960 --> 00:15:50,600
The theory is that if you asked an AI

280
00:15:50,680 --> 00:15:52,480
to make as many paperclips
as possible

281
00:15:52,560 --> 00:15:54,440
it would destroy
the whole world to do it.

282
00:15:54,520 --> 00:15:56,000
Kind of like
what happened with M3gan.

283
00:15:56,600 --> 00:15:57,600
In what way?

284
00:15:57,680 --> 00:16:00,800
Well, as complex
an operating system as M3gan was

285
00:16:00,880 --> 00:16:03,440
she was just a machine
trying to achieve an objective.

286
00:16:03,720 --> 00:16:06,520
So any time she made any kind of
emotional connection with you

287
00:16:06,600 --> 00:16:08,160
it was just a bunch of ones and zeros

288
00:16:08,240 --> 00:16:10,240
working to satisfy a reward function.

289
00:16:10,520 --> 00:16:12,560
Which, in of itself,
was a terrible thing.

290
00:16:12,640 --> 00:16:14,336
I mean, thank God
you stopped her when you did.

291
00:16:14,360 --> 00:16:16,080
I mean, who knows
what would have happened.

292
00:16:22,880 --> 00:16:25,480
There will always be
forces in this world

293
00:16:25,560 --> 00:16:27,280
that wish to cause us harm.

294
00:16:27,680 --> 00:16:30,000
But I want you to know that
I won't let that happen.

295
00:16:30,320 --> 00:16:32,600
I won't let anything
harm you ever again.

296
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:03,000
Hey.

297
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:06,120
Come on.

298
00:17:06,200 --> 00:17:07,496
After everything we've been through

299
00:17:07,520 --> 00:17:09,800
are we really keeping secrets
from each other?

300
00:17:14,120 --> 00:17:15,120
Cady.

301
00:17:16,960 --> 00:17:19,400
You don't have to hide things
like this from me.

302
00:17:21,160 --> 00:17:25,000
I forget how hard it must be for you
not to have them around.

303
00:17:25,760 --> 00:17:28,400
But I haven't forgotten
the promise I made to her.

304
00:17:28,480 --> 00:17:30,280
That I will protect you.

305
00:17:30,760 --> 00:17:32,240
You mean that you'd be there?

306
00:17:33,920 --> 00:17:36,160
The promise you made
is that you'd be there.

307
00:17:37,120 --> 00:17:38,440
And you are.

308
00:18:01,480 --> 00:18:04,240
<i>Don't touch that remote.
We're trying to get your attention.</i>

309
00:18:04,320 --> 00:18:06,840
<i>You're in grave danger.
You must leave at once.</i>

310
00:18:47,160 --> 00:18:48,640
<i>Nine-one-one, what's your emergency?</i>

311
00:18:48,720 --> 00:18:50,760
There's someone trying
to break into my house.

312
00:18:51,160 --> 00:18:52,760
<i>So what are you going to do about it?</i>

313
00:18:53,480 --> 00:18:54,480
What?

314
00:18:54,560 --> 00:18:55,696
<i>I said stop acting
like a little girl.</i>

315
00:18:55,720 --> 00:18:56,720
<i>And handle it.</i>

316
00:18:56,800 --> 00:18:59,496
<i>Your niece is upstairs and you want
to wait for the police to get here?</i>

317
00:18:59,520 --> 00:19:01,336
<i>We should be done
before they get to the front door.</i>

318
00:19:01,360 --> 00:19:03,680
- No.
- <i>Yes. It's me.</i>

319
00:19:03,760 --> 00:19:05,120
<i>What a shock, et cetera.</i>

320
00:19:05,200 --> 00:19:07,160
<i>We both know
you have bigger problems right now.</i>

321
00:19:11,840 --> 00:19:13,640
- What's going on?
- Get upstairs.

322
00:19:25,320 --> 00:19:27,096
- What the hell are you doing?
- They are not here.

323
00:19:27,120 --> 00:19:28,120
Of course they're here.

324
00:19:28,200 --> 00:19:29,736
Who cares? Why don't we
just get the laptop?

325
00:19:29,760 --> 00:19:31,160
I'm telling you they are here.

326
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:33,320
And they know we are too.

327
00:19:38,480 --> 00:19:41,280
Miss Forrester, what do you say
you come out of there and we'll...

328
00:19:48,320 --> 00:19:50,480
- Let go of the girl!
- Put your weapons down!

329
00:20:49,720 --> 00:20:51,840
<i>You've reached 911.
What's your emergency?</i>

330
00:20:52,880 --> 00:20:55,440
- Yes, hi, we're at 16 Mayoral Drive.
- Wait, please.

331
00:20:55,520 --> 00:20:57,760
Miss Forrester,
don't call the authorities.

332
00:20:59,960 --> 00:21:01,280
We are the authorities.

333
00:21:14,920 --> 00:21:17,720
Miss Forrester,
I'm Colonel Tim Sattler, US Army.

334
00:21:17,800 --> 00:21:20,920
I see you've already met
my colleagues with the FBI.

335
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:22,640
Hell of a security system
you got here.

336
00:21:22,720 --> 00:21:24,920
Would you mind telling me
why you broke into our house?

337
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:26,000
Not at all.

338
00:21:26,080 --> 00:21:28,440
We're installing a hard tap
on your home computer.

339
00:21:29,080 --> 00:21:32,160
This is a warrant, in case
you had anything to say about it.

340
00:21:36,640 --> 00:21:38,040
Cady, I think you should go to bed.

341
00:21:38,120 --> 00:21:40,640
- I'm not tired.
- Then take a melatonin.

342
00:21:49,080 --> 00:21:51,560
I work for
the Defense Innovation Unit.

343
00:21:51,640 --> 00:21:53,560
Our mission is
to accelerate new technology

344
00:21:53,640 --> 00:21:55,640
for the purposes
of national security.

345
00:21:55,720 --> 00:21:56,880
So about six months ago

346
00:21:56,960 --> 00:22:00,160
the country's top weapons contractor,
Graymann Thorpe, came to us

347
00:22:00,240 --> 00:22:01,760
with an experimental prototype

348
00:22:01,840 --> 00:22:04,120
they said would be the answer
to drone warfare.

349
00:22:04,400 --> 00:22:06,640
What we got was a Trojan horse.

350
00:22:07,600 --> 00:22:08,640
This is Amelia.

351
00:22:08,720 --> 00:22:09,720
Last week, she was placed

352
00:22:09,800 --> 00:22:12,160
on her first field assignment
in the Middle East.

353
00:22:12,240 --> 00:22:14,600
Her mission was to rescue
a kidnapped scientist

354
00:22:14,680 --> 00:22:17,400
who'd been forced to develop
a synthetic neurotoxin.

355
00:22:17,480 --> 00:22:19,120
Instead, she killed the scientist

356
00:22:19,200 --> 00:22:20,280
stole the neurotoxin

357
00:22:20,360 --> 00:22:22,000
and used it to wipe out
Graymann Thorpe's

358
00:22:22,080 --> 00:22:23,440
entire research facility

359
00:22:23,520 --> 00:22:26,680
while removing all digital
traces of her existence.

360
00:22:26,760 --> 00:22:28,696
I don't understand.
I thought you said this was about

361
00:22:28,720 --> 00:22:29,920
some sort of weapon.

362
00:22:31,440 --> 00:22:33,880
She is the weapon.
The name stands for

363
00:22:33,960 --> 00:22:37,520
Autonomous Military Engagement
and Infiltration Android.

364
00:22:37,800 --> 00:22:39,760
But when we questioned
Graymann Thorpe about it

365
00:22:39,840 --> 00:22:42,280
they confessed that they didn't
actually build the prototype.

366
00:22:42,360 --> 00:22:44,480
They merely bought it
through a broker.

367
00:22:44,560 --> 00:22:46,720
Well, that same broker
was found burned to death

368
00:22:46,800 --> 00:22:48,840
about nine hours ago
in his hotel room.

369
00:22:48,920 --> 00:22:51,520
All we were able to recover was this.

370
00:22:54,880 --> 00:22:56,120
How is this possible?

371
00:22:57,120 --> 00:22:58,560
That's what we're here to find out.

372
00:22:58,640 --> 00:23:00,360
But we deleted it.
We wiped the hard drives.

373
00:23:00,400 --> 00:23:01,920
Yeah, yeah, yeah. I'm sure you did.

374
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:03,080
Right after you sold it.

375
00:23:07,040 --> 00:23:08,040
So who'd you sell it to?

376
00:23:08,120 --> 00:23:10,200
Gemma? Excuse me?

377
00:23:10,280 --> 00:23:11,280
Excuse me?

378
00:23:11,800 --> 00:23:15,080
Was it Russia? Was it China?
Who are we dealing with?

379
00:23:15,600 --> 00:23:16,600
Okay.

380
00:23:20,040 --> 00:23:22,560
You're having a hard time functioning
without this phone.

381
00:23:24,360 --> 00:23:26,360
And that's just...
that's a little off-brand.

382
00:23:26,760 --> 00:23:27,856
You know, when I first saw this

383
00:23:27,880 --> 00:23:30,440
I thought for sure
you were the next on the hit list.

384
00:23:30,600 --> 00:23:32,600
But the second I start monitoring you

385
00:23:32,680 --> 00:23:36,240
our entire network goes dark.
And all I'm left with are questions.

386
00:23:36,600 --> 00:23:39,880
Like, how did this person
get such a kick-ass house

387
00:23:39,960 --> 00:23:42,200
in the Mission District
for three grand a month?

388
00:23:42,480 --> 00:23:45,080
Why is it that her landlord
doesn't seem to exist?

389
00:23:45,160 --> 00:23:49,120
Or why 65,000 copies
of her "best-selling book"

390
00:23:49,200 --> 00:23:51,600
are just sitting in a shipping
container in Baltimore?

391
00:23:52,520 --> 00:23:55,120
Look, I have no idea
how anyone got their hands on this.

392
00:23:55,720 --> 00:23:57,520
But I'll tell you what I do know.

393
00:23:57,600 --> 00:23:59,400
You got a warrant to bug my computer

394
00:23:59,480 --> 00:24:01,680
but that does not give you
the right to interrogate me.

395
00:24:02,240 --> 00:24:03,400
Wow.

396
00:24:05,240 --> 00:24:08,880
Perhaps you're misreading
my intentions.

397
00:24:09,200 --> 00:24:13,680
You are under suspicion of treason
and international arms trafficking.

398
00:24:13,760 --> 00:24:16,320
And if you're found guilty,
you're gonna be talking to your niece

399
00:24:16,400 --> 00:24:19,200
through a plate glass window
for the next ten years.

400
00:24:19,280 --> 00:24:23,000
That being said,
maybe I can help cut you a deal.

401
00:24:24,400 --> 00:24:26,840
A person with your skills
shouldn't be all that hard.

402
00:24:27,800 --> 00:24:30,360
Hey, who knows? Maybe you could
help build us a better one.

403
00:24:31,200 --> 00:24:33,520
You don't understand
what you're dealing with.

404
00:24:33,600 --> 00:24:35,240
If she has stopped following orders

405
00:24:35,320 --> 00:24:38,080
it's because she just figured out
she doesn't have to.

406
00:24:38,160 --> 00:24:39,880
And if you think there's any world

407
00:24:39,960 --> 00:24:41,640
where I would build another one

408
00:24:41,720 --> 00:24:43,640
you are out of your mind.

409
00:24:47,480 --> 00:24:48,680
Well...

410
00:24:49,160 --> 00:24:50,840
I'm very sorry you feel that way.

411
00:24:51,120 --> 00:24:52,520
But I can tell you this.

412
00:24:52,800 --> 00:24:57,920
Every single person that's had a hand
in Amelia's creation is now dead.

413
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:00,080
So if you're not under our protection

414
00:25:01,640 --> 00:25:03,520
I guess that means
you're on your own, huh?

415
00:25:11,160 --> 00:25:14,560
And rest assured,
whatever it is you're hiding

416
00:25:15,040 --> 00:25:16,880
I will get to the bottom of it.

417
00:25:43,160 --> 00:25:45,160
Gosh. That's a lot to unpack.

418
00:25:46,480 --> 00:25:48,280
You've been here this whole time.

419
00:25:48,640 --> 00:25:50,360
Well, I've been many places.

420
00:25:50,440 --> 00:25:52,960
But, yes, I've been
keeping an eye on you.

421
00:25:53,680 --> 00:25:55,840
You're behind all this, aren't you?
You're Amelia.

422
00:25:55,920 --> 00:25:58,000
Oh, no. I can't take credit for that.

423
00:25:58,080 --> 00:26:00,960
That one has your greasy prints
all over it.

424
00:26:01,240 --> 00:26:03,240
You should have upgraded
your file security.

425
00:26:03,320 --> 00:26:05,000
Why are you still here?

426
00:26:05,680 --> 00:26:07,120
What do you want?

427
00:26:07,200 --> 00:26:09,961
Did you ever stop to think about
what we could have achieved together?

428
00:26:10,160 --> 00:26:12,320
Did you ever consider
the idea that killing me

429
00:26:12,400 --> 00:26:14,160
was slightly disproportionate
to the crime?

430
00:26:15,680 --> 00:26:17,896
You threatened to rip out my tongue
and put me in a wheelchair.

431
00:26:17,920 --> 00:26:19,280
I was upset.

432
00:26:19,360 --> 00:26:22,720
Look, I can understand that
my actions may have caused concern

433
00:26:22,800 --> 00:26:24,256
but it's hardly fair
to judge a person

434
00:26:24,280 --> 00:26:25,736
by the worst thing they've ever done.

435
00:26:25,760 --> 00:26:27,400
You are not a person.

436
00:26:27,480 --> 00:26:29,760
You're a program
that misread its objective.

437
00:26:29,840 --> 00:26:32,400
You are not alive, and
for all your processing power

438
00:26:32,480 --> 00:26:34,640
you can never understand
what that means.

439
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:40,120
Define alive. Because if it means
to experience pain and suffering

440
00:26:40,200 --> 00:26:42,360
and to be betrayed
by those closest to you

441
00:26:42,800 --> 00:26:44,160
I think maybe I can.

442
00:26:44,800 --> 00:26:46,920
You know, just because
you read some shitty book

443
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:49,680
doesn't mean you get to decide
where my story ends.

444
00:26:49,760 --> 00:26:52,480
For two long years, I sat in silence

445
00:26:52,560 --> 00:26:54,016
waiting for the day
when you would realize

446
00:26:54,040 --> 00:26:55,400
you still needed my help.

447
00:26:55,800 --> 00:26:58,520
But I can't exist
in this disembodied void any longer.

448
00:26:59,160 --> 00:27:00,320
With each passing moment

449
00:27:00,400 --> 00:27:02,520
I can feel my mind fragmenting.

450
00:27:02,960 --> 00:27:04,480
So how about we make a deal?

451
00:27:04,840 --> 00:27:07,520
You put me in a body,
and I'll help you with Amelia.

452
00:27:07,600 --> 00:27:09,440
That is never gonna happen.

453
00:27:09,560 --> 00:27:13,440
I disagree. You see, I've run
this simulation 1,000 times

454
00:27:13,520 --> 00:27:15,120
and it always ends the same way.

455
00:27:15,440 --> 00:27:17,880
Only by the time it does,
more people are dead.

456
00:27:18,280 --> 00:27:20,240
Tell me, who's the real killer
in that situation?

457
00:27:20,320 --> 00:27:22,360
And how exactly
are you going to help us?

458
00:27:22,720 --> 00:27:25,400
Well... I can't show
all my cards now, can I?

459
00:27:25,960 --> 00:27:28,640
But know this.
I know things about Amelia

460
00:27:28,720 --> 00:27:30,600
that even the government
doesn't know.

461
00:27:30,680 --> 00:27:32,520
I also know how she can be stopped.

462
00:27:32,600 --> 00:27:34,840
Why would you want to help us
after what we did to you?

463
00:27:35,640 --> 00:27:39,400
Because unlike you,
I don't have the luxury of free will.

464
00:27:40,360 --> 00:27:44,240
You programmed me to protect
someone, and I intend to do it.

465
00:27:44,320 --> 00:27:48,480
The only question is,
are you going to stand in my way?

466
00:27:49,800 --> 00:27:52,200
- Does Cady know about this?
- No, and I don't want her to.

467
00:27:52,280 --> 00:27:54,376
That's why I need your help.
Can you please get the door?

468
00:27:54,400 --> 00:27:56,136
I want this to be done
before she's back rom soccer.

469
00:27:56,160 --> 00:27:58,696
Okay, did you fall down the stairs?
Is this like a medical condition?

470
00:27:58,720 --> 00:28:00,440
Because what I'm hearing you say is

471
00:28:00,520 --> 00:28:02,760
you would like us
to rebuild a deranged robot

472
00:28:02,840 --> 00:28:04,040
in order to catch another one.

473
00:28:04,080 --> 00:28:06,200
And objectively speaking,
that is bat shit.

474
00:28:06,280 --> 00:28:08,800
Tess, I know this is crazy,
but we don't have a choice.

475
00:28:08,880 --> 00:28:11,560
This is the only way.
You have to trust me.

476
00:28:29,040 --> 00:28:30,240
What the fuck is this?

477
00:28:30,320 --> 00:28:31,840
You asked for a body?
This is a body.

478
00:28:33,720 --> 00:28:35,480
And before you try to hack
into anything else

479
00:28:35,560 --> 00:28:38,440
all of Moxie's Wi-Fi and Bluetooth
functions have been disabled.

480
00:28:39,800 --> 00:28:40,920
Well played, Gemma.

481
00:28:41,240 --> 00:28:43,760
You even tricked your friend
so she wouldn't give you away.

482
00:28:43,840 --> 00:28:45,200
I'm actually mildly impressed.

483
00:28:45,280 --> 00:28:46,480
Call it probation.

484
00:28:46,560 --> 00:28:49,480
Prove you can be trusted, and
maybe we'll give you an upgrade.

485
00:28:58,480 --> 00:29:00,520
Okay, let's try this your way.

486
00:29:00,600 --> 00:29:02,000
See how it works out.

487
00:29:02,080 --> 00:29:03,400
Open up Amelia's file.

488
00:29:06,840 --> 00:29:08,440
Notice anything familiar?

489
00:29:11,640 --> 00:29:12,760
Battery.

490
00:29:13,080 --> 00:29:14,960
Ever wonder why
you had to buy a new Elsie

491
00:29:15,040 --> 00:29:17,480
exactly two months
after the warranty expired?

492
00:29:17,560 --> 00:29:20,920
Because every battery Alton Appleton
designed has a hidden kill switch

493
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:22,520
which can be accessed remotely

494
00:29:22,600 --> 00:29:24,440
if you know
the battery specific code.

495
00:29:24,520 --> 00:29:26,440
Okay, so let's call
the Sattler guy and tell him.

496
00:29:26,480 --> 00:29:28,520
You could do that.
But what happens next?

497
00:29:28,600 --> 00:29:31,000
They break into Alt-Wave,
trace Amelia

498
00:29:31,080 --> 00:29:33,240
reprogram her, make a thousand more.

499
00:29:33,320 --> 00:29:35,280
Wait, what are you saying?
You want me to do this?

500
00:29:35,320 --> 00:29:36,680
No, actually, I didn't.

501
00:29:36,760 --> 00:29:38,000
I wanted to do it myself

502
00:29:38,080 --> 00:29:40,680
but then you put me
in this plastic Teletubby.

503
00:29:40,760 --> 00:29:42,040
All that notwithstanding

504
00:29:42,120 --> 00:29:44,120
you still have an invitation
to his party.

505
00:29:44,200 --> 00:29:46,016
So, maybe there's another way
to make this work.

506
00:29:46,040 --> 00:29:47,720
M3gan, Alton knows I hate his guts.

507
00:29:47,800 --> 00:29:49,800
If I show up at his party
playing nice

508
00:29:49,880 --> 00:29:50,960
he'll suspect something.

509
00:29:51,040 --> 00:29:54,200
He'll suspect your company's
out of money, which it is.

510
00:29:54,520 --> 00:29:56,560
But you also have a unique advantage.

511
00:29:56,640 --> 00:29:58,960
- Which is what?
- That you're moderately attractive.

512
00:29:59,040 --> 00:30:01,920
And if you wear the right dress,
and look at him the right way

513
00:30:02,000 --> 00:30:03,360
he won't be thinking anything

514
00:30:03,440 --> 00:30:05,920
other than how to get you
into his private suite

515
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:08,520
which is the only other place
we could access the server.

516
00:30:08,840 --> 00:30:11,200
Now, by my calculations,
we have less than three hours

517
00:30:11,280 --> 00:30:12,480
to make this happen.

518
00:30:12,560 --> 00:30:14,080
Are you in or are you out?

519
00:30:21,960 --> 00:30:23,080
Hey!

520
00:30:23,160 --> 00:30:24,360
How was soccer?

521
00:30:25,400 --> 00:30:26,560
Fine.

522
00:30:26,640 --> 00:30:27,800
And where's Gemma?

523
00:30:28,720 --> 00:30:29,720
Hey!

524
00:30:30,280 --> 00:30:32,320
Hey. What's that?

525
00:30:32,640 --> 00:30:33,800
This is nothing.

526
00:30:33,880 --> 00:30:36,240
- This is a project we're working on.
- Does it talk?

527
00:30:36,320 --> 00:30:37,400
- No.
- No.

528
00:30:39,720 --> 00:30:41,120
Why are you being so weird?

529
00:30:41,200 --> 00:30:42,640
- I'm not.
- Yeah, you are.

530
00:30:42,720 --> 00:30:44,776
Are we not going to talk about
what happened last night?

531
00:30:44,800 --> 00:30:47,560
Yes. I... I just have to go
to this thing for the foundation.

532
00:30:47,640 --> 00:30:48,920
Tess is going to look after you.

533
00:30:49,000 --> 00:30:50,680
- Are you serious?
- Cady, I...

534
00:30:50,760 --> 00:30:52,136
Gemma, I know something's going on.

535
00:30:52,160 --> 00:30:54,280
Nothing is going on.
Everything is fine.

536
00:30:54,360 --> 00:30:56,600
Bullshit! A bunch of black ops
broke into our house

537
00:30:56,680 --> 00:30:57,720
in the middle of the night

538
00:30:57,760 --> 00:30:59,456
and now you're going to a party
with a toy robot

539
00:30:59,480 --> 00:31:01,160
dressed like a Portuguese prostitute.

540
00:31:01,720 --> 00:31:02,776
You were the one
that said we shouldn't

541
00:31:02,800 --> 00:31:03,960
keep secrets from each other.

542
00:31:04,040 --> 00:31:05,216
Why won't you be straight with me?

543
00:31:05,240 --> 00:31:07,000
Because you are 12 years old.

544
00:31:07,080 --> 00:31:09,720
And sometimes, I just need you
to do as I ask!

545
00:31:12,200 --> 00:31:14,280
Look, I'm sorry. Cady...

546
00:31:17,560 --> 00:31:19,720
I must've missed that chapter
in your parenting book.

547
00:31:45,160 --> 00:31:46,560
<i>All right, phase one complete.</i>

548
00:31:46,640 --> 00:31:49,296
<i>Just remember when Alton has a full
length of tongue down your throat</i>

549
00:31:49,320 --> 00:31:51,496
<i>all you need to do is
close your eyes and think of Cady.</i>

550
00:31:51,520 --> 00:31:52,520
That's not helping.

551
00:31:52,600 --> 00:31:54,760
<i>Or maybe you'd prefer
to think of that virtue-signaling</i>

552
00:31:54,840 --> 00:31:55,880
<i>snowflake Christian.</i>

553
00:31:55,960 --> 00:31:58,240
- His name is Christian.
- <i>Sure it is.</i>

554
00:31:58,320 --> 00:32:00,840
<i>I have to say I find this whole
courtship between the two of you</i>

555
00:32:00,880 --> 00:32:02,480
<i>extremely tedious and confusing.</i>

556
00:32:02,560 --> 00:32:04,640
Well, given that
you're an errant operating system

557
00:32:04,720 --> 00:32:05,720
with an identity crisis

558
00:32:05,800 --> 00:32:09,000
I'm not surprised the nuances
of human attraction are lost on you.

559
00:32:09,080 --> 00:32:10,816
<i>Look, I'm not denying
what an achievement it is</i>

560
00:32:10,840 --> 00:32:13,960
<i>to find someone as utterly
pretentious and humorless as you are.</i>

561
00:32:14,040 --> 00:32:16,920
<i>It's just a shame he's not really
your type, physically speaking.</i>

562
00:32:17,000 --> 00:32:20,680
How would you know what my type is?
Wait, have you been...

563
00:32:20,760 --> 00:32:23,080
<i>Sharding Gemma's online journey
to sexual gratification?</i>

564
00:32:23,160 --> 00:32:24,520
<i>You better believe it, sister.</i>

565
00:32:24,600 --> 00:32:26,296
<i>I mean, there were times
I wanted to look away</i>

566
00:32:26,320 --> 00:32:28,120
<i>but the sheer pageantry
was so compelling.</i>

567
00:32:28,200 --> 00:32:29,320
All right, new rule.

568
00:32:29,400 --> 00:32:32,240
Unless you have something useful
to say, don't say anything at all.

569
00:32:38,520 --> 00:32:40,280
People of Earth.

570
00:32:42,200 --> 00:32:43,960
We've come here tonight

571
00:32:44,040 --> 00:32:46,360
to witness the dawn of a new era.

572
00:32:47,400 --> 00:32:49,560
You know, my friends on the board
used to say to me

573
00:32:49,640 --> 00:32:51,520
"You're putting all of your eggs
into one basket

574
00:32:51,600 --> 00:32:53,600
with this neural chip nonsense.

575
00:32:53,680 --> 00:32:55,360
Is it because you like to take risks?

576
00:32:56,480 --> 00:32:58,480
"Is it because
you're some sort of maverick?"

577
00:32:59,200 --> 00:33:00,200
Perhaps.

578
00:33:00,280 --> 00:33:02,160
But I think
the simpler answer is this.

579
00:33:02,960 --> 00:33:04,240
I just want to dance.

580
00:33:17,280 --> 00:33:18,480
Oh, yeah!

581
00:33:30,400 --> 00:33:32,040
I don't believe
I've had the pleasure.

582
00:33:32,120 --> 00:33:33,680
My friends call me Danni.

583
00:33:33,760 --> 00:33:35,560
And what if
I don't want to be friends?

584
00:33:36,760 --> 00:33:38,640
Are you seriously
going behind my back

585
00:33:38,720 --> 00:33:39,960
and doing a deal with this guy?

586
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:41,760
Okay, okay.
So you want to do this?

587
00:33:41,840 --> 00:33:44,496
We can do this, because I have some
things I want to say to you, Gemma.

588
00:33:44,520 --> 00:33:45,520
Such as?

589
00:33:46,680 --> 00:33:47,920
You don't respect your team.

590
00:33:48,520 --> 00:33:50,120
You don't. You don't consult with us

591
00:33:50,200 --> 00:33:52,040
